===Etymology 2===
Origin uncertain, either
* from (notably northern) English dialect {{term|lake}}/{{term|laik||to play}} (c.1300, from {{etyl|non}} {{term|leika|lang=non||to play (as opposed to work)}}), with intrusive -r- common in southern British dialect; or
* shortening of {{term|skylark}} (1809), sailors' slang, "play roughly in the rigging of a ship", because the common European larks were proverbial for high-flying; Dutch has a similar idea in {{term|speelvogel||playbird, a person of markedly playful nature|lang=nl}}.

